📅 DAY 25 — QUERY DESIGN + STACK THINKING + VALIDATION
🧠 1) QUERY PARAMS — FLEXIBLE, SAFE READ APIs
🔥 Core Idea

Query params define how clients access data:

GET /transactions?user_id=U1&status=SUCCESS&from=2026-01-01&to=2026-01-31&limit=50&cursor=abc&sort=ts_desc

👉 You’re designing a query language over HTTP.

🧠 Deep Concepts (GS-Level)
✔ API as a Query Interface
Support filtering, sorting, pagination
Avoid breaking changes (extensible via params)

💬 Top Answer:

“I treat query params as a stable query interface, enabling flexible access patterns without changing endpoints.”

✔ Filtering Strategy (Push Down)
Apply filters as early as possible (DB layer)
Align filters with indexes (e.g., user_id, ts)

💬 Top Answer:

“I push filtering to the database and align parameters with indexes to minimize data scanned and reduce latency.”

✔ Pagination (Cursor > Offset at Scale)
Offset: simple, degrades with large offsets
Cursor: stable, scalable (use last seen key)

💬 Top Answer:

“For large datasets, I prefer cursor-based pagination to avoid performance issues and ensure stable ordering.”

✔ Sorting & Determinism
Always define stable sort order (e.g., ts, id)
Prevent duplicates/missing rows across pages

💬 Top Answer:

“I ensure deterministic sorting with a tie-breaker to keep pagination consistent.”

✔ Validation & Guardrails
Cap limit (e.g., max 100–200)
Validate enums (status), ranges (from <= to)
Reject unsupported combinations

💬 Top Answer:

“I validate query params strictly and enforce limits to protect the system from expensive queries.”

✔ Caching
GET is cache-friendly
Use ETag/Cache-Control or Redis for hot queries

💬 Top Answer:

“I leverage caching for read-heavy endpoints to reduce DB load and improve latency.”

⚙️ FastAPI (filters + validation + pagination)
from fastapi import FastAPI, Query, HTTPException
from typing import Optional

app = FastAPI()

@app.get("/transactions")
async def get_tx(
    user_id: Optional[str] = None,
    status: Optional[str] = Query(None, pattern="^(SUCCESS|FAILED)$"),
    limit: int = Query(50, ge=1, le=200),
    cursor: Optional[str] = None,
    sort: str = Query("ts_desc", pattern="^(ts_asc|ts_desc)$"),
):
    # validate combos
    if cursor and sort == "ts_asc":
        raise HTTPException(400, "Cursor incompatible with ascending order")

    # pseudo: push filters to DB, apply cursor
    return {"data": [], "next_cursor": None}
🎯 Scenarios (Query Params)
API returns too much data
💬 “Enforce pagination, cap limits, add filters.”
Slow queries
💬 “Add indexes aligned to filters/sort; push filters to DB; cache hot queries.”
Inconsistent paging
💬 “Use cursor pagination with deterministic ordering (include tie-breaker).”
🧠 GS-Level Summary

“I design query params as a flexible query interface with filtering, sorting, and cursor-based pagination, validate inputs strictly, and align with DB indexes and caching for performance.”

🧠 2) DSA — STACK (CONTROL FLOW & PARSING)
🔥 Core Idea

Stack models LIFO control flow:

push → push → pop → pop

👉 Mirrors call stack, parsing, and state rollback.

🧠 Deep Concepts
✔ When to use a stack
Nested structures (parentheses, JSON/XML)
Backtracking/undo
Monotonic constraints (next greater/smaller)
✔ Classic: Valid Parentheses
def is_valid(s):
    st, mp = [], {')':'(', ']':'[', '}':'{'}
    for ch in s:
        if ch in mp.values():
            st.append(ch)
        else:
            if not st or st.pop() != mp[ch]:
                return False
    return not st
✔ Monotonic Stack (VERY IMPORTANT)
Maintain increasing/decreasing stack
Solve Next Greater Element, Stock Span, Largest Rectangle

💬 Top Answer:

“I use a monotonic stack to process elements once and maintain order constraints, achieving linear time.”

✔ Complexity Thinking
Each element pushed and popped at most once → O(n)
⚙️ Real Usage
Compilers/parsers (syntax checking)
Expression evaluation
Undo/redo systems
Time-series analytics (spans, ranges)
🎯 Scenarios (Stack)
Parsing expressions fails on nested input
💬 “Use a stack to track context and validate structure.”
Need next greater element fast
💬 “Use monotonic stack to get O(n) instead of O(n²).”
Memory concerns
💬 “Stack is O(n); ensure constraints or stream processing if needed.”
🧠 GS-Level Summary

“Stacks model LIFO control flow and are ideal for nested parsing and monotonic constraints, enabling linear-time solutions for many sequence problems.”

⚙️ 3) PRODUCTION — VALIDATION (DEFENSE-IN-DEPTH)
🔥 Core Idea

Validation is your first reliability and security layer:

Reject bad input early → protect system
🧠 Deep Concepts
✔ Layers of Validation
Schema (types, formats) — Pydantic
Business rules (limits, invariants) — service layer
Security (sanitization, injection prevention) — DB/ORM, escaping

💬 Top Answer:

“I apply validation at multiple layers—schema at the API boundary, business rules in services, and security at the persistence layer.”

✔ Fail Fast + Clear Errors
Return 4xx with structured body
Do not proceed with partial data
✔ Guardrails
Cap sizes (limit, payload size)
Whitelist enums
Validate ranges (from <= to)
Rate limiting (429)
✔ Don’t Trust the Client
Re-validate even if UI validates
Use parameterized queries to avoid SQL injection
